      "content": "A sourdough starter should be bubbling and growing after feeding it, but it can sometimes take a little longer to show signs of activity. It's possible that your kitchen temperature, while not too low, may not be ideal for your starter to thrive. Sourdough starters prefer a warmer environment, around 70-75 degrees Fahrenheit. You could try placing your starter in a warmer spot, like near a radiator or in a turned-on oven with the light on. Also, make sure you're using fresh, high-quality flour and water when feeding your starter. If it still doesn't show signs of activity, you might want to try starting over with a new batch. Remember, patience is key with sourdough starters – they can sometimes be a bit finicky. Keep an eye on it and don't get discouraged!",
